<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-differentiability-classes"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Differentiability Classes</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Continuity and differentiability come in layers. A function may be
      differentiable without having a continuous derivative, and a function
      may have many derivatives without having one more. This leads to the
      standard hierarchy of classes <m>C^n</m> and <m>D^n</m>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <p>
    Let <m>I \subseteq \R</m> be an open interval.
    For <m>n \in \N</m>, let <m>D^n(I)</m> be the set of functions
    <m>f \colon I \to \R</m> that are <term><m>n</m> times differentiable</term><idx>differentiability classes</idx>
    on <m>I</m>, and let <m>C^n(I)</m> be the set of functions whose
    <m>n</m>-th derivative exists and is continuous on <m>I</m>. We also set
    <m>C^0(I)</m> equal to the set of continuous functions on <m>I</m>.
  </p>

  <proposition xml:id="prop-differentiability-class-hierarchy">
    <title>The Hierarchy of Differentiability Classes</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        For every open interval <m>I</m>,
        <me>
          C^0(I) \supseteq D^1(I) \supseteq C^1(I) \supseteq D^2(I)
          \supseteq C^2(I) \supseteq \cdots.
        </me>
        If we define
        <me>
          C^\infty(I):=\bigcap_{n=0}^\infty C^n(I),
        </me>
        then also
        <me>
          C^\infty(I)=\bigcap_{n=1}^\infty D^n(I).
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        The inclusion <m>D^1(I) \subseteq C^0(I)</m> is just the fact that
        differentiability implies continuity
        (<xref ref="prop-differentiable-implies-continuous"/>). More
        generally, if <m>f \in D^{n+1}(I)</m>, then <m>f^{(n)}</m> is
        differentiable on <m>I</m>, hence continuous. Therefore
        <m>f \in C^n(I)</m>, so
        <me>
          D^{n+1}(I) \subseteq C^n(I)
        </me>
        for every <m>n \ge 0</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        On the other hand, if <m>f \in C^n(I)</m>, then by definition
        <m>f^{(n)}</m> exists, so certainly <m>f \in D^n(I)</m>. Thus
        <me>
          C^n(I) \subseteq D^n(I)
        </me>
        for every <m>n \ge 1</m>. Chaining these inclusions gives the stated
        hierarchy.
      </p>

      <p>
        Since <m>D^{n+1}(I) \subseteq C^n(I) \subseteq D^n(I)</m> for each
        <m>n \ge 1</m>, a function belongs to every <m>C^n(I)</m> if and only
        if it belongs to every <m>D^n(I)</m>. This proves the identity for
        <m>C^\infty(I)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </proposition>

  <p>
    The inclusions in
    <xref ref="prop-differentiability-class-hierarchy"/> are all strict. The
    first strict inclusion already appears in
    <xref ref="eg-inverse-function-theorem-needs-derivative-continuity"/>:
    there exists a differentiable function whose derivative is not
    continuous at <m>0</m>. The next two examples show that this phenomenon
    persists at every order.
  </p>

  <example xml:id="eg-c-n-minus-1-not-d-n">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each <m>n \ge 1</m>, define
        <me>
          f_n(x)=\begin{cases}
          x^n &amp; \text{if } x \ge 0,\\
          -x^n &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Then
        <me>
          f_n \in C^{n-1}(\R) \setminus D^n(\R).
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        For <m>0 \le k \le n-1</m> and <m>x \ne 0</m>, repeated
        differentiation gives
        <me>
          f_n^{(k)}(x)=\begin{cases}
          \dfrac{n!}{(n-k)!}x^{n-k} &amp; \text{if } x \gt 0,\\
          -\dfrac{n!}{(n-k)!}x^{n-k} &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Since <m>n-k \ge 1</m>, both one-sided limits at <m>0</m> are equal
        to <m>0</m>. So each derivative up to order <m>n-1</m> extends
        continuously across <m>0</m>. Hence <m>f_n \in C^{n-1}(\R)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        For <m>x \ne 0</m>, the <m>n</m>-th derivative is
        <me>
          f_n^{(n)}(x)=\begin{cases}
          n! &amp; \text{if } x \gt 0,\\
          -n! &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        The left and right limits at <m>0</m> are different, so
        <m>f_n^{(n)}(0)</m> does not exist. Therefore
        <m>f_n \notin D^n(\R)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </example>

  <example xml:id="eg-d-n-not-c-n">
    <statement>
      <p>
        For each <m>n \ge 1</m>, define
        <me>
          g_n(x)=\begin{cases}
          x^{2n}\sin(1/x) &amp; \text{if } x \ne 0,\\
          0 &amp; \text{if } x=0.
          \end{cases}
        </me>
        Then
        <me>
          g_n \in D^n(\R) \setminus C^n(\R).
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>

    <proof>
      <p>
        We claim that, for each <m>k=0,1,\dots,n</m>, the derivative
        <m>g_n^{(k)}(x)</m> for <m>x \ne 0</m> is a finite linear combination
        of terms of the form
        <me>
          x^m \sin(1/x)
          \qquad \text{and} \qquad
          x^m \cos(1/x),
        </me>
        where <m>m \ge 2n-2k</m>. This is true for <m>k=0</m>. If it holds for
        some <m>k</m>, then differentiating one such term either lowers the
        power of <m>x</m> by <m>1</m> or by <m>2</m>, so after one more
        differentiation all exponents are still at least
        <m>2n-2(k+1)</m>. Thus the claim follows by induction.
      </p>

      <p>
        In particular, if <m>k \le n-1</m>, then every exponent that occurs is
        at least <m>2</m>. Hence
        <m>g_n^{(k)}(x) \to 0</m> as <m>x \to 0</m>. Therefore
        <m>g_n^{(k)}(0)=0</m>, and
        <me>
          \frac{g_n^{(k)}(h)-g_n^{(k)}(0)}{h}
          =
          \frac{g_n^{(k)}(h)}{h}
          \to 0
          \qquad \text{as } h \to 0,
        </me>
        because every term in <m>g_n^{(k)}(h)/h</m> still has a positive power
        of <m>h</m>. Thus <m>g_n^{(k+1)}(0)</m> exists and equals <m>0</m>.
        By induction, <m>g_n \in D^n(\R)</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        After differentiating exactly <m>n</m> times, there is a term with
        power <m>x^0</m>: it comes from differentiating the trigonometric
        factor in every step. So <m>g_n^{(n)}(x)</m> has the form
        <me>
          g_n^{(n)}(x)=A(x)+B(x)\sin(1/x)+C(x)\cos(1/x)
        </me>
        for <m>x \ne 0</m>, where <m>A,B,C</m> are finite linear combinations
        of powers of <m>x</m> and at least one of <m>B(0)</m> or <m>C(0)</m>
        is nonzero. Consequently, <m>g_n^{(n)}(x)</m> oscillates as
        <m>x \to 0</m> and is not continuous at <m>0</m>. Hence
        <m>g_n \notin C^n(\R)</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
  </example>

  <p>
    Later, in <xref ref="sec-analytic-functions"/>, we will meet analytic
    functions. Every analytic function belongs to <m>C^\infty</m>, but the
    example above shows that belonging to <m>C^\infty</m> is still not enough
    to force a function to agree with a power series.
  </p>
</section>
